You can use the `pattern` attribute in HTML to specify a regular expression that the input field's value must match. Here's an example of how to create an input field that requires a number to follow the 'XXX-XX-XXXX' format:

```html
<input type="text" id="phone-number" name="phone-number" pattern="[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{4}" title="Format: XXX-XX-XXXX">
```

In this example:

- `[0-9]{3}` matches exactly 3 digits.
- `-` matches a hyphen.
- `[0-9]{2}` matches exactly 2 digits.
- `-` matches a hyphen.
- `[0-9]{4}` matches exactly 4 digits.

However, this will not prevent the user from entering invalid characters. To achieve this, you can use JavaScript to add an event listener to the input field and validate the input on each key press.

Here's an example of how to do this:

```javascript
const phoneNumberInput = document.getElementById('phone-number');

phoneNumberInput.addEventListener('input', () => {
  const value = phoneNumberInput.value;
  const pattern = /^[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{4}$/;
  if (!pattern.test(value)) {
    phoneNumberInput.value = value.replace(/[^0-9-]/g, '');
  }
});
```

In this example, the `input` event is used to listen for changes to the input field's value. The regular expression `^[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{4}$` is used to match the input against the desired pattern. If the input does not match the pattern, the `replace` method is used to remove any invalid characters.

You can also use the `oninput` event in HTML to achieve the same result:

```html
<input type="text" id="phone-number" name="phone-number" pattern="[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{4}" title="Format: XXX-XX-XXXX" oninput="this.value = this.value.replace(/[^0-9-]/g, '')">
```

This will automatically remove any invalid characters from the input field as the user types.
